# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spatial-audio-hrtf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] 3-D audio (processing) is the spatial domain convolution of sound waves using head-related transfer functions.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] It is the phenomenon of transforming sound waves (using head-related transfer function or HRTF filters and cross talk cancellation techniques) to mimic natural sounds waves, which emanate from a point in a 3-D space.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] It allows trickery of the brain using the ears and auditory nerves, pretending to place different sounds in different 3-D locations upon hearing the sounds, even though the sounds may just be produced from only two speakers (dissimilar to surround sound).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] Using head-related transfer functions and reverberation, the changes of sound on its way from the source (including reflections from walls and floors) to the listener's ear can be simulated.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] These effects include localization of sound sources behind, above and below the listener.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] Some 3D technologies also convert binaural recordings to stereo recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] 3D Positional Audio effects emerged in the 1990s in PC and video game consoles.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] 3D audio techniques have also been incorporated in music and video-game style music video arts.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] True representation of the elevation level for 3D loudspeaker reproduction become possible by the Ambisonics and wave field synthesis (WFS) principle.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] Some amusement parks have created attractions based around the principles of 3-D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] One example is *Sounds Dangerous!* at Disney's Hollywood Studios at the Walt Disney World Resort in Florida.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] Guests wear special earphones as they watch a short film starring comedian Drew Carey.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] At a point in the film, the screen goes dark while a 3-D audio sound-track immerses the guests in the ongoing story.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] To ensure that the effect is heard properly, the earphone covers are color-coded to indicate how they should be worn.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] This is not a generated effect but a binaural recording.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] Nick Cave's novel *The Death of Bunny Munro* was recorded in audiobook format using 3D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] The song "Propeller Seeds" by English artist Imogen Heap was recorded using 3D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] There have been developments in using 3D audio for DJ performances including the world's first Dolby Atmos event on 23 January 2016 held at Ministry of Sound, London.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] The event was a showcase of a 3D audio DJ set performed by Hospital Records owner Tony Colman aka London Elektricity.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] Other investigations included the Jago 3D Sound project which is looking at using Ambisonics combined with STEM music containers created and released by Native Instruments in 2015 for 3D nightclub sets.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] In November 2024 it was announced that the US Air Force had awarded a $9 million contract to Danish defense company Terma A/S, to supply its 3-D audio system for the F-16 Fighting Falcon aircraft, with a program of upgrades over the next two years.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/3d-audio-effect] The system will provide high-fidelity digital audio by spatially separating radio signals, aligning audio with threat directions, and integrating active noise reduction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The term "binaural" has frequently been confused as a synonym for the word "stereo", due in part to systematic use in the mid-1950s by the recording industry, as a marketing buzzword.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Conventional stereo recordings do not factor in natural ear spacing or "head shadow" of the head and ears, since these things happen naturally as a person listens, generating interaural time differences (ITDs) and interaural level differences (ILDs) specific to their listening position.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The history of binaural recording goes back to 1881.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The first binaural unit, the théâtrophone, was invented by Clément Ader.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It consisted of an array of spaced pairs of carbon pencil microphones installed along the front edge of the Opera Garnier.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The signal was sent to subscribers through the telephone system, and required that they hold a headset up to each ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In the early 1930s, several binaural heads were developed.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] One, referred to as "Oscar" was made by Bell Labs, using 1.4 in (36 mm) microphones inserted into the cheeks of a mannequin's head, and was demonstrated at the World Fair in Chicago, in 1933.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The Dutch firm, Philips, also developed a binaural head, with the microphones located at the ears, which produced a better result.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] These early adaptations of the mannequins used in shops to model clothes led to the moniker "dummy head".
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Over the course of the 20th century, advancements in microphone design and an understanding of the significance that the anatomy of the human ear played in the localization of sound led to further developments in the design of binaural heads.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Their use ranged from acoustic analysis, such as to record word scoring for speech intelligibility measurement, hearing aid design, for music reproduction, and radio drama.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In 1974, Virgin Records issued the first solo album by Tangerine Dream's leader Edgar Froese, titled *Aqua*.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The sleeve notes inform listeners that the tracks *NGC 891* and *Upland* were recorded using a binaural head system developed by Gunther Brunschen.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Listeners were advised to listen with stereo headphones.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Although Edgar was keen to continue to use this system for subsequent recordings, it was abandoned because although it worked well through headphones, the improved sound quality did not translate adequately to a hi-fi speaker system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In 1972, Neumann released the KU80 binaural head, which would eventually lead to the KU100 binaural head, which is widely used today.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In 1978, Lou Reed released the first commercially produced binaural pop record, *Street Hassle*, a combination of live and studio recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Binaural sound did not take off for music reproduction for consumers due to the expensive, specialized equipment required for quality recordings, and the requirement of headphones for proper reproduction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Particularly in pre-Walkman days, most consumers considered headphones an inconvenience, and were only interested in recordings that could be listened to on a home stereo system or in automobiles.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Lastly, the types of things that can be recorded do not have a typically high market value.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Popular music typically involves a lot of electro-acoustic sources such as guitars and keyboards that when recorded in a studio setting would have little benefit from being recorded binaurally.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Recordings that are of interest are live orchestral performances, and ambient "environmental" recordings of city sounds, nature, and other such subject matters.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] During the 1990s, electronic devices which used digital signal processing (DSP) to reproduce HRTFs were made commercially available.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] These devices allowed the sound engineer to make it sound like a monophonic sound had been recorded with a binaural head, adjusting the apparent direction and proximity of a sound in real time.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] They were unusual and expensive, but would allow the sound engineer to alter special effects of prerecorded sounds quickly and conveniently.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Software versions of these are now widely available.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The modern era has seen a resurgence of interest in binaural, partially due to the increased use of headphones, cheaper methods of recording and the general increased commercial interest in 360° audio technology.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In 2005, *Aqua* was remixed for limited edition reissue in Germany and Japan, with an additional track *Upland Dawn* appended to the end of the CD.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In 2015, Singaporean singer-songwriter JJ Lin released his debut experimental album *From M.E. to Myself*, using dummy head recording.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] This is also the first full album in the pop music industry to use this technology.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The show toured the world, and played on Broadway for several months, winning a Tony Award for its sound design.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Binaural sound is often used in Virtual Reality, to help the user locate the source of something outside their field of vision.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It also helps the user feel immersed in the experience by creating a realistic sonic landscape.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Typically, this form of binaural sound is created by using monophonic recordings of sound that are processed through a binaural panner (and other processes that simulate distance, occlusion and acoustics) in real-time, based on where the user is facing.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The online ASMR community has widely employed binaural recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Many of the major music streaming services have started offering "Spatial Audio" versions of popular music.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] These are often mixed using Dolby Atmos, which combines cinematic-style surround sound panning with object based panning.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] A smart phone, tablet or computer can be used to listen to these with headphones and the music track will be rendered into binaural sound on playback.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Devices like Apple's AirPods Pro can be used to track the rotation of the users head and allow the music sources to rotate around the listener as they rotate their head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The increasing popularity of podcasts has seen an increase in audio drama production, and there have been many produced using binaural recording, or by recording in mono and mixing those recordings using Dolby Atmos.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The simplest recording technique utilizes two small microphones, placed inside the ears of a human, a technique that can create very impressive first-person perspective recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The DPA 4560 was produced specifically for this type of recording.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] This technique also clearly picks up the sounds of the person wearing the microphones, their breathing, clothing rustle, and any shifts in movement they may make, which can make it impractical for many types of recording.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] More common is using a binaural head, also known as a dummy head, or *Kunstkopf*.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] These typically have two microphones, 15 cm (5.9 in) apart, facing away from each other, with a head shaped mass between them.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Typically these microphones will be embedded within the head with a silicone mould of a pair of ears in front of them.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Some binaural microphones go further and include elements of the human torso, aiming to simulate how sounds are reflected off the shoulders and absorbed by body mass, known as Head and Torso Simulators (HATS).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] They often include more intricate detail, such as a mouth simulator.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The distance between the ears, the size, weight and shape of the head and ears aim to roughly approximate those of an average human, though as very few people are actually the average size this explains some of the variance in how dramatically a binaural effect is heard by different people.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The aim is that each microphone records sound in the same spatial relationship: each signal having the relative inter-aural time, level and timbral differences that the two ears of a human being would have if they were situated in the same position as the binaural head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The recordings are then listened to through headphones, with the microphone from the left ear of the binaural head routed into the left headphone of the listener, and the microphone from the right ear routed into the right headphone of the listener.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Our brains are then able to interpret the spatial cues within the recordings to create a three-dimensional soundscape within our consciousness because it mirrors our own hearing system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Like our ears, a binaural head records sounds from all directions: all the sounds of a space and a clear impression of the room acoustics.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] A binaural head can create exceptional recordings of acoustic music concerts, for example.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] However, it will also clearly record any noises the audience make too.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] A binaural head also mirrors the limitations of the human hearing system too. so for example when a sound is directly in front of us. there is very little difference between the sound hitting our left ear and our right ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] If a sound is directly behind us, again there is very little difference between the sound hitting our left ear and our right ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Without the help of our visual system, we can struggle to tell if something is directly in front of us, or directly behind us, based on our hearing system alone.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Designed to be used in-situ for electro-acoustic tests on, for example, telephone handsets, headsets, audio conference devices, microphones, headphones, hearing aids and hearing protectors.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It includes soft moulded pinnae, nose, mouth and torso.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Using an MRI scanner, Brüel & Kjær and DTU collected the geometries of a large population of human ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] By capturing the full ear canal geometry including the bony part adjoining the eardrum was, this data was post-processed to determine the average human ear canal geometry.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The Neumann KU 100 is a simple design, with a more abstract representation of a head, and "realistic" ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The Neumann is a commonly used binaural microphone and features use by BBC R&D teams.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] KEMAR is designed using large statistical research to as close to the average human measurements as possible.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Torso reflections have been seen to be a considerable contributor to creating a successful binaural recording.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It has replaceable pinnae of different sizes and materials and sets of different type ear-canal simulators.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The 3Dio range of binaural microphones feature two silicone ear (pinna) moulds separated by 14 centimetres (5.5 in)—slightly narrower than many binaural microphones.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Microphones are placed inside the ears, and range from Primo EM172 in the Free Space and Free Space XLR models, to DPA 4060s in the Pro II model.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The 3Dio range is considerably cheaper than the Neumann KU 100, for example, and used more on a consumer to prosumer level.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] There is no head mass between the ears, which allows the microphone to be lighter and more mobile, compared to other binaural microphones which can often weigh several kilograms.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] These are both in-ear wearable stereo microphones, used like earphones, placed inside the human pinna.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] They use the user's pinna and head mass to create the binaural effect.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Sounds that have been recorded in mono can be placed in a three-dimensional soundstage as if they had been recorded using a binaural head by using "binaural panning" software.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The sound is processed using a complex mathematical algorithm imprinting inter-aural time, level, limited HRTF information, and optionally also room acoustics, onto the sound recording creating a binaural effect.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Ambisonic recording techniques can also be used to generate binaural sound recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The technique of binaural re-recording is simple but has not been well established.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It follows the same principles of Worldizing, a technique used by film sound designers in which sound is played over a loudspeaker in a real-world location and then re-recorded, taking along all the aspects and characteristics of the real-world environment with it.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] A binaural microphone is used to record content being played over a multi-channel speaker set-up.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The binaural head, or microphone, is therefore theoretically making a recording of how humans will hear multi-channel content.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The soundtrack to a film, for example, could be recorded by the binaural microphone with all the environmental cues of the given location, as well as reverberations.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The main focus of recording with a binaural head is to achieve a perfect binaural playback that is suited to all listeners.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The problem arises that each human head has different shaped and sized features, making it very difficult to create a binaural effect compatible for everyone's ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Averaging is done, either in the physical properties of binaural head microphones, or in the mathematical algorithm used to generate binaural sound using binaural panning software or ambisonic decoders.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Some people may report hearing a very dramatic soundstage, while others may not.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The effect that the shape of our head and our ears has on the sound we hear is part of what is called the Head Related Transfer Function, or HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Recent Apple iPhone Pro's use the phone's camera and LiDAR Scanner to create a 3D picture of the listener's ears, in order to create a personalized HRTF file so that their own ear shape is factored into what they hear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] In January 2012 BBC R&D worked together with BBC Radio 4 to produce a binaural production of *Private Peaceful*.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The dramatization featured a reproduction of a 5.1 speaker system, and had 4 variations.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] At the start of each variation, the listener would hear a series of test signals allowing for a choice of which version gives them the best spatial experience.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] By doing this, BBC R&D have accepted that there will be variations on the success of the binaural reproduction, and therefore provided different mixes based on different sets of HRTF data.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The release of *Private Peaceful* had an accompanying survey which all listeners were asked to complete.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It asked questions about the success that the binaural reproduction had with the listeners and which version (1–4) the listener thought was most successful.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] During an interview with Chris Pike from BBC R&D in September 2012, Pike stated that "you may get good spatial impression but timbral coloration is often an issue".
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Francis Rumsey states in the 2011 article "Whose head is it anyway?" that "badly implemented HRTFs can give rise to poor timbral quality, poor externalisation, and a host of other unwanted results".
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Getting the HRTF data correct is a key point in making the final product a success, and possibly by making the HRTF data as extensive as possible, there will be less room for error such as timbral issues.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] The HRTFs used for *Private Peaceful* were designed by measuring impulse responses in a reverberant room, done so to capture a sense of space, but is not very external and there are obvious timbral issues as pointed out by Pike.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Juha Merimaa from Sennheiser Research Laboratories found that using HRTF filters to reduce timbral issues did not affect the spatial localization previously achieved using the data when tested on a panel of listeners.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] This explains that there are ways of reducing the effects of timbral issues on audio that have been processed with HRTF data, but this does mean further EQ manipulation of the audio.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Consideration will have to be taken into how much manipulation is appropriate and to what extent, if any, will this affect the end users experience.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Ideal listening conditions will most likely be experienced with headphones designed to give an as flat frequency response as possible in order to reduce colouration of the audio the user is listening to.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] But many people may only have access to low quality headphones, which can result in them hearing something very different from what was intended, and that can muddy the spatial cues in the binaural audio.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] While a binaural recording can be played on a stereo loudspeaker system, the spatial cues that should only be heard by the left ear are heard by both ears, rather than only by the ear on the corresponding side, as would be the case with headphones.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] Likewise, with the right ear spatial cues.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] This means the spatial effect of the binaural sound is compromised to a degree, and in some cases can sound a little odd.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/binaural-recording] It is possible to convert binaural sound into a format that sits more naturally on a stereo loudspeaker system using software, such as Logic Pro's Binaural Post Processing plug-in.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] A **head-related transfer function** (**HRTF**) is a response that characterizes how an ear receives a sound from a point in space.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] As sound strikes the listener, the size and shape of the head, ears, ear canal, density of the head, size and shape of nasal and oral cavities, all transform the sound and affect how it is perceived, boosting some frequencies and attenuating others.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Generally speaking, the HRTF boosts frequencies from 2–5 kHz with a primary resonance of +17 dB at 2,700 Hz.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] But the response curve is more complex than a single bump, affects a broad frequency spectrum, and varies significantly from person to person.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] A pair of HRTFs for two ears can be used to synthesize a binaural sound that seems to come from a particular point in space.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] It is a transfer function, describing how a sound from a specific point will arrive at the ear (generally at the outer end of the auditory canal).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Some consumer home entertainment products designed to reproduce surround sound from stereo (two-speaker) headphones use HRTFs.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Some forms of HRTF processing have also been included in computer software to simulate surround sound playback from loudspeakers.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Humans have just two ears, but can locate sounds in three dimensions – in range (distance), in direction above and below (elevation), in front and to the rear, as well as to either side (azimuth).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] This is possible because the brain, inner ear, and the external ears (pinna) work together to make inferences about location.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Humans estimate the location of a source by taking cues derived from one ear (*monaural cues*), and by comparing cues received at both ears (*difference cues* or *binaural cues*).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Among the difference cues are time differences of arrival and intensity differences.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The monaural cues come from the interaction between the sound source and the human anatomy, in which the original source sound is modified before it enters the ear canal for processing by the auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] These modifications encode the source location and may be captured via an impulse response which relates the source location and the ear location.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] This impulse response is termed the *head-related impulse response* (HRIR).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Convolution of an arbitrary source sound with the HRIR converts the sound to that which would have been heard by the listener if it had been played at the source location, with the listener's ear at the receiver location.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] HRIRs have been used to produce virtual surround sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF is the Fourier transform of HRIR.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] HRTFs for left and right ear (expressed above as HRIRs) describe the filtering of a sound source (*x*(*t*)) before it is perceived at the left and right ears as *x*L(*t*) and *x*R(*t*), respectively.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF can also be described as the modifications to a sound from a direction in free air to the sound as it arrives at the eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] These modifications include the shape of the listener's outer ear, the shape of the listener's head and body, the acoustic characteristics of the space in which the sound is played, and so on.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] All these characteristics will influence how (or whether) a listener can accurately tell what direction a sound is coming from.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] In the AES69-2015 standard, the Audio Engineering Society (AES) has defined the SOFA file format for storing spatially oriented acoustic data like head-related transfer functions (HRTFs).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] SOFA software libraries and files are collected at the Sofa Conventions website.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The associated mechanism varies between individuals, as their head and ear shapes differ.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] HRTF describes how a given sound wave input (parameterized as frequency and source location) is filtered by the diffraction and reflection properties of the head, pinna, and torso, before the sound reaches the transduction machinery of the eardrum and inner ear (see auditory system).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Biologically, the source-location-specific prefiltering effects of these external structures aid in the neural determination of source location, particularly the determination of the source's elevation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Linear systems analysis defines the transfer function as the complex ratio between the output signal spectrum and the input signal spectrum as a function of frequency.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Blauert (1974; cited in Blauert, 1981) initially defined the transfer function as the free-field transfer function (FFTF).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Other terms include free-field to eardrum transfer function and the pressure transformation from the free-field to the eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Less specific descriptions include the pinna transfer function, the outer ear transfer function, the pinna response, or directional transfer function (DTF).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] One method used to obtain the HRTF from a given source location is therefore to measure the head-related impulse response (HRIR), *h*(*t*), at the ear drum for the impulse *Δ*(*t*) placed at the source.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF *H*(*f*) is the Fourier transform of the HRIR *h*(*t*).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Even when measured for a "dummy head" of idealized geometry, HRTF are complicated functions of frequency and the three spatial variables.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] For distances greater than 1 m from the head, however, the HRTF can be said to attenuate inversely with range.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] It is this far field HRTF, *H*(*f*, *θ*, *φ*), that has most often been measured.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] At closer range, the difference in level observed between the ears can grow quite large, even in the low-frequency region within which negligible level differences are observed in the far field.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] HRTFs are typically measured in an anechoic chamber to minimize the influence of early reflections and reverberation on the measured response.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] HRTFs are measured at small increments of *θ* such as 15° or 30° in the horizontal plane, with interpolation used to synthesize *HRTF*s for arbitrary positions of *θ*.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Even with small increments, however, interpolation can lead to front-back confusion, and optimizing the interpolation procedure is an active area of research.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] In order to maximize the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) in a measured HRTF, it is important that the impulse being generated be of high volume.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] In practice, however, it can be difficult to generate impulses at high volumes and, if generated, they can be damaging to human ears, so it is more common for HRTFs to be directly calculated in the frequency domain using a frequency-swept sine wave or by using maximum length sequences.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] User fatigue is still a problem, however, highlighting the need for the ability to interpolate based on fewer measurements.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The head-related transfer function is involved in resolving the cone of confusion, a series of points where interaural time difference (ITD) and interaural level difference (ILD) are identical for sound sources from many locations around the *0* part of the cone.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] When a sound is received by the ear it can either go straight down the ear into the ear canal or it can be reflected off the pinnae of the ear, into the ear canal a fraction of a second later.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Essentially, the brain is looking for frequency notches in the signal that correspond to particular known directions of sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] If another person's ears were substituted, the individual would not immediately be able to localize sound, as the patterns of enhancement and cancellation would be different from those patterns the person's auditory system is used to.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] However, after some weeks, the auditory system would adapt to the new head-related transfer function.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The inter-subject variability in the spectra of HRTFs has been studied through cluster analyses.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Assessing the variation through changes between the person's ear, we can limit our perspective with the degrees of freedom of the head and its relation with the spatial domain.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Through this, we eliminate the tilt and other co-ordinate parameters that add complexity.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] For the purpose of calibration we are only concerned with the direction level to our ears, ergo a specific degree of freedom.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] A basic assumption in the creation of a virtual auditory space is that if the acoustical waveforms present at a listener's eardrums are the same under headphones as in free field, then the listener's experience should also be the same.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Typically, sounds generated from headphones are perceived as originating from within the head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] In the virtual auditory space, the headphones should be able to "externalize" the sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Using the HRTF, sounds can be spatially positioned using the technique described below.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Let *x*1(*t*) represent an electrical signal driving a loudspeaker and *y*1(*t*) represent the signal received by a microphone inside the listener's eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Similarly, let *x*2(*t*) represent the electrical signal driving a headphone and *y*2(*t*) represent the microphone response to the signal.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The goal of the virtual auditory space is to choose *x*2(*t*) such that *y*2(*t*) = *y*1(*t*).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] where *L* is the transfer function of the loudspeaker in the free field, *F* is the HRTF, *M* is the microphone transfer function, and *H* is the headphone-to-eardrum transfer function.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Therefore, theoretically, if *x*1(*t*) is passed through this filter and the resulting *x*2(*t*) is played on the headphones, it should produce the same signal at the eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Since the filter applies only to a single ear, another one must be derived for the other ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] This process is repeated for many places in the virtual environment to create an array of head-related transfer functions for each position to be recreated while ensuring that the sampling conditions are set by the Nyquist criteria.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] There is less reliable phase estimation in the very low part of the frequency band, and in the upper frequencies the phase response is affected by the features of the pinna.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Earlier studies also show that the HRTF phase response is mostly linear and that listeners are insensitive to the details of the interaural phase spectrum as long as the interaural time delay (ITD) of the combined low-frequency part of the waveform is maintained.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] This is the modeled phase response of the subject HRTF as a time delay, dependent on the direction and elevation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] A scaling factor is a function of the anthropometric features.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] For example, a training set of N subjects would consider each HRTF phase and describe a single ITD scaling factor as the average delay of the group.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] This computed scaling factor can estimate the time delay as function of the direction and elevation for any given individual.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Converting the time delay to phase response for the left and the right ears is trivial.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF phase can be described by the ITD scaling factor.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] This is in turn quantified by the anthropometric data of a given individual taken as the source of reference.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] that represents the subject's anthropometric features as a linear superposition of the anthropometric features from the training data (y' = βT X), and then apply the same sparse vector directly on the scaling vector H.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] where The ITD scaling factors for all persons in the dataset are stacked in a vector *H* ∈ ***R****N*, so the value *H**n* corresponds to the scaling factor of the n-th person.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] We solve the above minimization problem using least absolute shrinkage and selection operator.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] We assume that the HRTFs are represented by the same relation as the anthropometric features.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] where The HRTFs for each subject are described by a tensor of size *D* × *K*, where *D* is the number of HRTF directions and *K* is the number of frequency bins.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] All *H**n*,*d*,*k* corresponds to all the HRTFs of the training set are stacked in a new tensor *H* ∈ ***R****N*×*D*×*K*, so the value Hn,d,k corresponds to the *k*-th frequency bin for *d*-th HRTF direction of the *n*-th person.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Also *H*'*d*,*k* corresponds to *k*-th frequency for every d-th HRTF direction of the synthesized HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Accumulation of HRTF data has made it possible for a computer program to infer an approximate HRTF from head geometry.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Two programs are known to do so, both open-source: Mesh2HRTF, which runs physical simulation on a full 3D-mesh of the head, and EAC, which uses a neural network trained from existing HRTFs and works from photo and other rough measurements.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The perceived accuracy of the result depends on how closely the HRTF data set matches the characteristics of one's own ears, though a generic HRTF may be preferred to an accurate one measured from one's one ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Some vendors like Apple and Sony offer a variety of HRTFs to be selected by the user's ear shape.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Windows 10 and above come with Microsoft Spatial Sound included, the same spatial audio framework used on Xbox One and Hololens 2.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] On a Windows PC or an Xbox One, the framework can use several different downstream audio processors, including Windows Sonic for Headphones, Dolby Atmos, and DTS Headphone:X, to apply an HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The framework can render both fixed-position surround sound sources and dynamic "object" sources that can move in space.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Apple similarly has Spatial Sound for its devices used with headphones produced by Apple or Beats.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] For music playback to headphones, Dolby Atmos can be enabled and the HRTF applied.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF (or rather, the object positions) can vary with head tracking to maintain the illusion of direction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Qualcomm Snapdragon has a similar head-tracked spatial audio system, used by some brands of Android phones.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] YouTube uses head-tracked HRTF with 360-degree and VR videos.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Linux is currently unable to directly process any of the proprietary spatial audio (surround plus dynamic objects) formats.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] SoundScape Renderer offers directional synthesis.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] PulseAudio and PipeWire each can provide virtual surround (fixed-location channels) using an HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Recent PipeWire versions are also able to provide dynamic spatial rendering using HRTFs, however integration with applications is still in progress.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Users can configure their own positional and dynamic sound sources, as well as simulate a surround speaker setup using existing configurations.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] The cross-platform OpenAL Soft, an implementation of OpenAL, uses HRTFs for improved localization.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/head-related-transfer-function] Windows and Linux spatial audio systems support any model of stereo headphones, while Apple only allows spatial audio to be used with Apple or Beats-branded Bluetooth headsets.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The **interaural time difference** (or **ITD**) when concerning humans or animals, is the difference in arrival time of a sound between two ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] It is important in the localization of sounds, as it provides a cue to the direction or angle of the sound source from the head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] If a signal arrives at the head from one side, the signal has further to travel to reach the far ear than the near ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This pathlength difference results in a time difference between the sound's arrivals at the ears, which is detected and aids the process of identifying the direction of sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] When a signal is produced in the horizontal plane, its angle in relation to the head is referred to as its azimuth, with 0 degrees (0°) azimuth being directly in front of the listener, 90° to the right, and 180° being directly behind.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The duplex theory proposed by Lord Rayleigh (1907) provides an explanation for the ability of humans to localise sounds by time differences between the sounds reaching each ear (ITDs) and differences in sound level entering the ears (interaural level differences, ILDs).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] But there still lies a question whether ITD or ILD is prominent.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The duplex theory states that ITDs are used to localise low-frequency sounds, in particular, while ILDs are used in the localisation of high-frequency sound inputs.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] A consequence of this duplex system is that it is also possible to generate so-called "cue trading" or "time–intensity trading" stimuli on headphones, where ITDs pointing to the left are offset by ILDs pointing to the right, so the sound is perceived as coming from the midline.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] A limitation of the duplex theory is that the theory does not completely explain directional hearing, as no explanation is given for the ability to distinguish between a sound source directly in front and behind.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Also the theory only relates to localising sounds in the horizontal plane around the head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The theory also does not take into account the use of the pinna in localisation (Gelfand, 2004).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Experiments conducted by Woodworth (1938) tested the duplex theory by using a solid sphere to model the shape of the head and measuring the ITDs as a function of azimuth for different frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The model used had a distance between the two ears of approximately 22–23 cm.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Initial measurements found that there was a maximum time delay of approximately 660 μs when the sound source was placed at directly 90° azimuth to one ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This time delay correlates to the wavelength of a sound input with a frequency of 1500 Hz.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The results concluded that when a sound played had a frequency less than 1500 Hz, the wavelength is greater than this maximum time delay between the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Therefore, there is a phase difference between the sound waves entering the ears providing acoustic localisation cues.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] With a sound input with a frequency closer to 1500 Hz the wavelength of the sound wave is similar to the natural time delay.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Therefore, due to the size of the head and the distance between the ears there is a reduced phase difference, so localisations errors start to be made.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] When a high-frequency sound input is used with a frequency greater than 1500 Hz, the wavelength is shorter than the distance between the ears, a head shadow is produced, and ILD provide cues for the localisation of this sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] (1957) also conducted experiments taking measurements on how ITDs alter with changing the azimuth of the loudspeaker around the head at different frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] But unlike the Woodworth experiments, human subjects were used rather than a model of the head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The experiment results agreed with the conclusion made by Woodworth about ITDs.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The experiments also concluded that there is no difference in ITDs when sounds are provided from directly in front or behind at 0° and 180° azimuth.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The explanation for this is that the sound is equidistant from both ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Interaural time differences alter as the loudspeaker is moved around the head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The maximum ITD of 660 μs occurs when a sound source is positioned at 90° azimuth to one ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Starting in 1948, the prevailing theory on interaural time differences centered on the idea that inputs from the medial superior olive differentially process inputs from the ipsilateral and contralateral side relative to the sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This is accomplished through a discrepancy in arrival time of excitatory inputs into the medial superior olive, based on differential conductance of the axons, which allows both sounds to ultimately converge at the same time through neurons with complementary intrinsic properties.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Franken et al. attempted to further elucidate the mechanisms underlying ITD in mammalian brains.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] One experiment they performed was to isolate discrete inhibitory post-synaptic potentials and try to determine whether inhibitory inputs to the superior olive were allowing the faster excitatory input to delay firing until the two signals were synced.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] However, after blocking EPSPs with a glutamate receptor blocker, they determine that the size of inhibitory inputs was too marginal to appear to play a significant role in phase locking.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This was verified when the experimenters blocked inhibitory input and still saw clear phase locking of the excitatory inputs in their absence.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This led them to the theory that in-phase excitatory inputs are summated such that the brain can process sound localization by counting the number of action potentials that arise from various magnitudes of summated depolarization.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Franken et al. also examined anatomical and functional patterns within the superior olive to clarify previous theories about the rostrocaudal axis serving as a source of tonotopy.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Their results showed a significant correlation between tuning frequency and relative position along the dorsoventral axis, while they saw no distinguishable pattern of tuning frequency on the rostrocaudal axis.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Lastly, they went on to further explore the driving forces behind the interaural time difference, specifically whether the process is simply the alignment of inputs that is processed by a coincidence detector, or whether the process is more complicated.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Evidence from Franken et al. shows that the processing is affected by inputs that precede the binaural signal, which would alter the functioning of voltage-gated sodium and potassium channels to shift the membrane potential of the neuron.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Furthermore, the shift is dependent on the frequency tuning of each neuron, ultimately creating a more complex confluence and analysis of sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] These findings provide several pieces of evidence that contradict existing theories about binaural audition.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The auditory nerve fibres, known as the afferent nerve fibres, carry information from the organ of Corti to the brainstem and brain.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Auditory afferent fibres consist of two types of fibres called type I and type II fibres.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Type I fibres innervate the base of one or two inner hair cells and Type II fibres innervate the outer hair cells.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Both leave the organ of Corti through an opening called the habenula perforata.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The type I fibres are thicker than the type II fibres and may also differ in how they innervate the inner hair cells.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Neurons with large calyceal endings ensure preservation of timing information throughout the ITD pathway.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Next in the pathway is the cochlear nucleus, which receives mainly ipsilateral (that is, from the same side) afferent input.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The cochlear nucleus has three distinct anatomical divisions, known as the antero-ventral cochlear nucleus (AVCN), postero-ventral cochlear nucleus (PVCN) and dorsal cochlear nucleus (DCN) and each have different neural innervations.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The AVCN contains predominant *bushy cells*, with one or two profusely branching dendrites; it is thought that bushy cells may process the change in the spectral profile of complex stimuli.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The AVCN also contain cells with more complex firing patterns than bushy cells called *multipolar cells*, these cells have several profusely branching dendrites and irregular shaped cell bodies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Multipolar cells are sensitive to changes in acoustic stimuli and in particular, onset and offset of sounds, as well as changes in intensity and frequency.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The axons of both cell types leave the AVCN as large tract called the *ventral acoustic stria*, which forms part of the trapezoid body and travels to the superior olivary complex.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] A group of nuclei in pons make up the superior olivary complex (SOC).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This is the first stage in auditory pathway to receive input from both cochleas, which is crucial for our ability to localise the sounds source in the horizontal plane.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The SOC receives input from cochlear nuclei, primarily the ipsilateral and contralateral AVCN.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Four nuclei make up the SOC but only the medial superior olive (MSO) and the lateral superior olive (LSO) receive input from both cochlear nuclei.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The MSO is made up of neurons which receive input from the low-frequency fibers of the left and right AVCN.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The result of having input from both cochleas is an increase in the firing rate of the MSO units.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The neurons in the MSO are sensitive to the difference in the arrival time of sound at each ear, also known as the interaural time difference (ITD).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Research shows that if stimulation arrives at one ear before the other, many of the MSO units will have increased discharge rates.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The lateral lemniscus (LL) is the main auditory tract in the brainstem connecting SOC to the inferior colliculus.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The dorsal nucleus of the lateral lemniscus (DNLL) is a group of neurons separated by lemniscus fibres, these fibres are predominantly destined for the inferior colliculus (IC).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The IC is situated in the midbrain and consists of a group of nuclei the largest of these is the central nucleus of inferior colliculus (CNIC).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The greater part of the ascending axons forming the lateral lemniscus will terminate in the ipsilateral CNIC however a few follow the commissure of Probst and terminate on the contralateral CNIC.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The axons of most of the CNIC cells form the brachium of IC and leave the brainstem to travel to the ipsilateral thalamus.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Cells in different parts of the IC tend to be monaural, responding to input from one ear, or binaural and therefore respond to bilateral stimulation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The spectral processing that occurs in the AVCN and the ability to process binaural stimuli, as seen in the SOC, are replicated in the IC.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Lower centres of the IC extract different features of the acoustic signal such as frequencies, frequency bands, onsets, offsets, changes in intensity and localisation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] A number of studies have looked into the effect of hearing loss on interaural time differences.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] In their review of localisation and lateralisation studies, Durlach, Thompson, and Colburn (1981), cited in Moore (1996) found a "clear trend for poor localization and lateralization in people with unilateral or asymmetrical cochlear damage".
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This is due to the difference in performance between the two ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] In support of this, they did not find significant localisation problems in individuals with symmetrical cochlear losses.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] In addition to this, studies have been conducted into the effect of hearing loss on the threshold for interaural time differences.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] The normal human threshold for detection of an ITD is up to a time difference of 10 μs.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] Studies by Gabriel, Koehnke, & Colburn (1992), Häusler, Colburn, & Marr (1983) and Kinkel, Kollmeier, & Holube (1991) (cited by Moore, 1996) have shown that there can be great differences between individuals regarding binaural performance.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] It was found that unilateral or asymmetric hearing losses can increase the threshold of ITD detection in patients.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] This was also found to apply to individuals with symmetrical hearing losses when detecting ITDs in narrowband signals.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/interaural-time-difference] However, ITD thresholds seem to be normal for those with symmetrical losses when listening to broadband sounds.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The sound localization mechanisms of the mammalian auditory system have been extensively studied.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The auditory system uses several cues for sound source localization, including time difference and level difference (or intensity difference) between the ears, and spectral information.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Other animals, such as birds and reptiles, also use them but they may use them differently, and some also have localization cues which are absent in the human auditory system, such as the effects of ear movements.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Animals with the ability to localize sound have an evolutionary advantage.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Sound is the perceptual result of mechanical vibrations traveling through a medium such as air or water.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Through the mechanisms of compression and rarefaction, sound waves travel through the air, bounce off the pinna and concha of the exterior ear, and enter the ear canal.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In vertebrates, interaural time differences are known to be calculated in the superior olivary nucleus of the brainstem.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] According to Jeffress, this calculation relies on delay lines: neurons in the superior olive which accept innervation from each ear with different connecting axon lengths.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Some cells are more directly connected to one ear than the other, thus they are specific for a particular interaural time difference.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This theory is equivalent to the mathematical procedure of cross-correlation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] However, because Jeffress's theory is unable to account for the precedence effect, in which only the first of multiple identical sounds is used to determine the sounds' location (thus avoiding confusion caused by echoes), it cannot be entirely used to explain the response.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Furthermore, a number of recent physiological observations made in the midbrain and brainstem of small mammals have shed considerable doubt on the validity of Jeffress's original ideas.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Neurons sensitive to interaural level differences (ILDs) are excited by stimulation of one ear and inhibited by stimulation of the other ear, such that the response magnitude of the cell depends on the relative strengths of the two inputs, which in turn, depends on the sound intensities at the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In the auditory midbrain nucleus, the inferior colliculus (IC), many ILD sensitive neurons have response functions that decline steeply from maximum to zero spikes as a function of ILD.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] However, there are also many neurons with much more shallow response functions that do not decline to zero spikes.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Sound localization is the process of determining the location of a sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The brain utilizes subtle differences in intensity, spectral, and timing cues to localize sound sources.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Localization can be described in terms of three-dimensional position: the azimuth or horizontal angle, the elevation or vertical angle, and the distance (for static sounds) or velocity (for moving sounds).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The azimuth of a sound is signaled by the difference in arrival times between the ears, by the relative amplitude of high-frequency sounds (the shadow effect), and by the asymmetrical spectral reflections from various parts of our bodies, including torso, shoulders, and pinnae.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The distance cues are the loss of amplitude, the loss of high frequencies, and the ratio of the direct signal to the reverberated signal.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Depending on where the source is located, our head acts as a barrier to change the timbre, intensity, and spectral qualities of the sound, helping the brain orient where the sound emanated from.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] These minute differences between the two ears are known as interaural cues.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Lower frequencies, with longer wavelengths, diffract the sound around the head forcing the brain to focus only on the phasing cues from the source.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Helmut Haas discovered that we can discern the sound source despite additional reflections at 10 decibels louder than the original wave front, using the earliest arriving wave front.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This principle is known as the Haas effect, a specific version of the precedence effect.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Haas measured down to even a 1 millisecond difference in timing between the original sound and reflected sound increased the spaciousness, allowing the brain to discern the true location of the original sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The nervous system combines all early reflections into a single perceptual whole allowing the brain to process multiple different sounds at once.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The nervous system will combine reflections that are within about 35 milliseconds of each other and that have a similar intensity.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In 1907, Lord Rayleigh utilized tuning forks to generate monophonic excitation and studied the lateral sound localization theory on a human head model without auricle.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] He first presented the interaural clue difference based sound localization theory, which is known as Duplex Theory.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Human ears are on different sides of the head, and thus have different coordinates in space.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] As shown in the duplex theory figure, since the distances between the acoustic source and ears are different, there are time difference and intensity difference between the sound signals of two ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] We call those kinds of differences as Interaural Time Difference (ITD) and Interaural Intensity Difference (IID) respectively.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] (ITD) between left ear (top) and right ear (bottom).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] (ILD) between left ear (left) and right ear (right).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] From the duplex theory figure we can see that for source B1 or source B2, there will be a propagation delay between two ears, which will generate the ITD.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Simultaneously, human head and ears may have a shadowing effect on high-frequency signals, which will generate IID.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For frequencies below 800 Hz, the dimensions of the head (ear distance 21.5 cm, corresponding to an interaural time delay of 626 μs) are smaller than the half wavelength of the sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] So the auditory system can determine phase delays between both ears without confusion.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Interaural level differences are very low in this frequency range, especially below about 200 Hz, so a precise evaluation of the input direction is nearly impossible on the basis of level differences alone.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] As the frequency drops below 80 Hz it becomes difficult or impossible to use either time difference or level difference to determine a sound's lateral source, because the phase difference between the ears becomes too small for a directional evaluation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For frequencies above 1600 Hz the dimensions of the head are greater than the length of the sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] An unambiguous determination of the input direction based on interaural phase alone is not possible at these frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] However, the interaural level differences become larger, and these level differences are evaluated by the auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This mechanism becomes especially important in reverberant environments.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] After a sound onset there is a short time frame where the direct sound reaches the ears, but not yet the reflected sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The auditory system uses this short time frame for evaluating the sound source direction, and keeps this detected direction as long as reflections and reverberation prevent an unambiguous direction estimation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The mechanisms described above cannot be used to differentiate between a sound source ahead of the hearer or behind the hearer; therefore additional cues have to be evaluated.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Duplex theory shows that ITD and IID play significant roles in sound localization, but they can only deal with lateral localization problems.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For example, if two acoustic sources are placed symmetrically at the front and back of the right side of the human head, they will generate equal ITDs and IIDs, in what is called the cone model effect.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] However, human ears can still distinguish between these sources.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Besides that, in natural sense of hearing, one ear alone, without any ITD or IID, can distinguish between them with high accuracy.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Due to the disadvantages of duplex theory, researchers proposed the pinna filtering effect theory.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The shape of the human pinna is concave with complex folds and asymmetrical both horizontally and vertically.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Reflected and direct waves generate a frequency spectrum on the eardrum, relating to the acoustic sources.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Then auditory nerves localize the sources using this frequency spectrum.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] These spectrum clues generated by the pinna filtering effect can be presented as a head-related transfer function (HRTF).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The corresponding time domain expressions are called the head-related impulse response (HRIR).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The HRTF is also described as the transfer function from the free field to a specific point in the ear canal.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] where L and R represent the left ear and right ear respectively, $P_{L}$ and $P_{R}$ represent the amplitude of the sound pressure at the entrances to the left and right ear canals, and $P_{0}$ is the amplitude of sound pressure at the center of the head coordinate when listener does not exist.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In general, an HRTF's $H_{L}$ and $H_{R}$ are functions of source angular position $\theta$ , elevation angle $\varphi$ , the distance between the source and the center of the head r , the angular velocity $\omega$ and the equivalent dimension of the head $\alpha$ .
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] At present, the main institutes that work on measuring HRTF database include CIPIC International Lab, MIT Media Lab, the Graduate School in Psychoacoustics at the University of Oldenburg, the Neurophysiology Lab at the University of Wisconsin–Madison and Ames Lab of NASA.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Databases of HRIRs from humans with normal and impaired hearing and from animals are publicly available.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The human outer ear, i.e. the structures of the pinna and the external ear canal, form direction-selective filters.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Depending on the sound input direction, different filter resonances become active.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] These resonances implant direction-specific patterns into the frequency responses of the ears, which can be evaluated by the auditory system for sound localization.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Together with other direction-selective reflections at the head, shoulders and torso, they form the outer ear transfer functions.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] These patterns in the ear's frequency responses are highly individual, depending on the shape and size of the outer ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] If sound is presented through headphones, and has been recorded via another head with different-shaped outer ear surfaces, the directional patterns differ from the listener's own, and problems will appear when trying to evaluate directions in the median plane with these foreign ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] As a consequence, front–back permutations or inside-the-head-localization can appear when listening to dummy head recordings, or otherwise referred to as binaural recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] It has been shown that human subjects can monaurally localize high frequency sound but not low frequency sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Binaural localization, however, was possible with lower frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This is likely due to the pinna being small enough to only interact with sound waves of high frequency.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] It seems that people can only accurately localize the elevation of sounds that are complex and include frequencies above 7,000 Hz, and a pinna must be present.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] When the head is stationary, the binaural cues for lateral sound localization (interaural time difference and interaural level difference) do not give information about the location of a sound in the median plane.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Identical ITDs and ILDs can be produced by sounds at eye level or at any elevation, as long as the lateral direction is constant.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] However, if the head is rotated, the ITD and ILD change dynamically, and those changes are different for sounds at different elevations.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For example, if an eye-level sound source is straight ahead and the head turns to the left, the sound becomes louder (and arrives sooner) at the right ear than at the left.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] But if the sound source is directly overhead, there will be no change in the ITD and ILD as the head turns.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Intermediate elevations will produce intermediate degrees of change, and if the presentation of binaural cues to the two ears during head movement is reversed, the sound will be heard behind the listener.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Hans Wallach artificially altered a sound's binaural cues during movements of the head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Although the sound was objectively placed at eye level, the dynamic changes to ITD and ILD as the head rotated were those that would be produced if the sound source had been elevated.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In this situation, the sound was heard at the synthesized elevation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The fact that the sound sources objectively remained at eye level prevented monaural cues from specifying the elevation, showing that it was the dynamic change in the binaural cues during head movement that allowed the sound to be correctly localized in the vertical dimension.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The head movements need not be actively produced; accurate vertical localization occurred in a similar setup when the head rotation was produced passively, by seating the blindfolded subject in a rotating chair.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] As long as the dynamic changes in binaural cues accompanied a perceived head rotation, the synthesized elevation was perceived.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In the 1960s Batteau showed the pinna also enhances horizontal localization.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The human auditory system has only limited possibilities to determine the distance of a sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In the close-up-range there are some indications for distance determination, such as extreme level differences (e.g. when whispering into one ear) or specific pinna (the visible part of the ear) resonances in the close-up range.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Sound processing of the human auditory system is performed in so-called critical bands.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The hearing range is segmented into 24 critical bands, each with a width of 1 Bark or 100 Mel.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For a directional analysis the signals inside the critical band are analyzed together.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The auditory system can extract the sound of a desired sound source out of interfering noise.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This allows the listener to concentrate on only one speaker if other speakers are also talking (the cocktail party effect).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] With the help of the cocktail party effect sound from interfering directions is perceived attenuated compared to the sound from the desired direction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The auditory system can increase the signal-to-noise ratio by up to 15 dB, which means that interfering sound is perceived to be attenuated to half (or less) of its actual loudness.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In enclosed rooms not only the direct sound from a sound source is arriving at the listener's ears, but also sound which has been reflected at the walls.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The auditory system analyses only the direct sound, which is arriving first, for sound localization, but not the reflected sound, which is arriving later (law of the first wave front).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] So sound localization remains possible even in an echoic environment.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This echo cancellation occurs in the Dorsal Nucleus of the Lateral Lemniscus (DNLL).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In order to determine the time periods, where the direct sound prevails and which can be used for directional evaluation, the auditory system analyzes loudness changes in different critical bands and also the stability of the perceived direction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] If there is a strong attack of the loudness in several critical bands and if the perceived direction is stable, this attack is in all probability caused by the direct sound of a sound source, which is entering newly or which is changing its signal characteristics.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This short time period is used by the auditory system for directional and loudness analysis of this sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] When reflections arrive a little bit later, they do not enhance the loudness inside the critical bands in such a strong way, but the directional cues become unstable, because there is a mix of sound of several reflection directions.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] As a result, no new directional analysis is triggered by the auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This first detected direction from the direct sound is taken as the found sound source direction, until other strong loudness attacks, combined with stable directional information, indicate that a new directional analysis is possible.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This kind of sound localization technique provides us the real virtual stereo system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] It utilizes "smart" manikins, such as KEMAR, to glean signals or use DSP methods to simulate the transmission process from sources to ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] After amplifying, recording and transmitting, the two channels of received signals will be reproduced through earphones or speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This localization approach uses electroacoustic methods to obtain the spatial information of the original sound field by transferring the listener's auditory apparatus to the original sound field.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The most considerable advantages of it would be that its acoustic images are lively and natural.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Also, it only needs two independent transmitted signals to reproduce the acoustic image of a 3D system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The representatives of this kind of system are SRS Audio Sandbox, Spatializer Audio Lab and Qsound Qxpander.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] They use HRTF to simulate the received acoustic signals at the ears from different directions with common binary-channel stereo reproduction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Therefore, they can simulate reflected sound waves and improve subjective sense of space and envelopment.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Since they are para-virtualization stereo systems, the major goal of them is to simulate stereo sound information.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Traditional stereo systems use sensors that are quite different from human ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Although those sensors can receive the acoustic information from different directions, they do not have the same frequency response of human auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Therefore, when binary-channel mode is applied, human auditory systems still cannot feel the 3D sound effect field.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] However, the 3D para-virtualization stereo system overcome such disadvantages.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] It uses HRTF principles to glean acoustic information from the original sound field then produce a lively 3D sound field through common earphones or speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Since the multichannel stereo systems require many reproduction channels, some researchers adopted the HRTF simulation technologies to reduce the number of reproduction channels.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] They use only two speakers to simulate multiple speakers in a multichannel system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This process is called as virtual reproduction.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Essentially, such approach uses both interaural difference principle and pinna filtering effect theory.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Unfortunately, this kind of approach cannot perfectly substitute the traditional multichannel stereo system, such as 5.1/7.1 surround sound system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] That is because when the listening zone is relatively larger, simulation reproduction through HRTFs may cause invert acoustic images at symmetric positions.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Since most animals have two ears, many of the effects of the human auditory system can also be found in other animals.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Therefore, interaural time differences (interaural phase differences) and interaural level differences play a role for the hearing of many animals.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] But the influences on localization of these effects are dependent on head sizes, ear distances, the ear positions and the orientation of the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Smaller animals like insects use different techniques as the separation of the ears are too small.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For the process of animals emitting sound to improve localization, a biological form of active sonar, see animal echolocation.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] If the ears are located at the side of the head, similar lateral localization cues as for the human auditory system can be used.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This means: evaluation of interaural time differences (interaural phase differences) for lower frequencies and evaluation of interaural level differences for higher frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The evaluation of interaural phase differences is useful, as long as it gives unambiguous results.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This is the case, as long as ear distance is smaller than half the length (maximal one wavelength) of the sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For animals with a larger head than humans the evaluation range for interaural phase differences is shifted towards lower frequencies, for animals with a smaller head, this range is shifted towards higher frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The lowest frequency which can be localized depends on the ear distance.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Animals with a greater ear distance can localize lower frequencies than humans can.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For animals with a smaller ear distance the lowest localizable frequency is higher than for humans.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] If the ears are located at the side of the head, interaural level differences appear for higher frequencies and can be evaluated for localization tasks.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For animals with ears at the top of the head, no shadowing by the head will appear and therefore there will be much less interaural level differences which could be evaluated.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Many of these animals can move their ears, and these ear movements can be used as a lateral localization cue.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For many mammals there are also pronounced structures in the pinna near the entry of the ear canal.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] As a consequence, direction-dependent resonances can appear, which could be used as an additional localization cue, similar to the localization in the median plane in the human auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] There are additional localization cues which are also used by animals.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For sound localization in the median plane (elevation of the sound) also two detectors can be used, which are positioned at different heights.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In animals, however, rough elevation information is gained simply by tilting the head, provided that the sound lasts long enough to complete the movement.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This explains the innate behavior of cocking the head to one side when trying to localize a sound precisely.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] To get instantaneous localization in more than two dimensions from time-difference or amplitude-difference cues requires more than two detectors.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The tiny parasitic fly *Ormia ochracea* has become a model organism in sound localization experiments because of its unique ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The animal is too small for the time difference of sound arriving at the two ears to be calculated in the usual way, yet it can determine the direction of sound sources with exquisite precision.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The tympanic membranes of opposite ears are directly connected mechanically, allowing resolution of sub-microsecond time differences and requiring a new neural coding strategy.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Ho showed that the coupled-eardrum system in frogs can produce increased interaural vibration disparities when only small arrival time and sound level differences were available to the animal's head.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Efforts to build directional microphones based on the coupled-eardrum structure are underway.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Most owls are nocturnal or crepuscular birds of prey.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Because they hunt at night, they must rely on non-visual senses.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Experiments by Roger Payne have shown that owls are sensitive to the sounds made by their prey, not the heat or the smell.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] In fact, the sound cues are both necessary and sufficient for localization of mice from a distant location where they are perched.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] For this to work, the owls must be able to accurately localize both the azimuth and the elevation of the sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Dolphins (and other odontocetes) rely on echolocation to aid in detecting, identifying, localizing, and capturing prey.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Dolphins can localize sounds both passively and actively (echolocation) with a resolution of about 1 deg.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Cross-modal matching (between vision and echolocation) suggests dolphins perceive the spatial structure of complex objects interrogated through echolocation, a feat that likely requires spatially resolving individual object features and integration into a holistic representation of object shape.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Although dolphins are sensitive to small, binaural intensity and time differences, mounting evidence suggests dolphins employ position-dependent spectral cues derived from well-developed head-related transfer functions, for sound localization in both the horizontal and vertical planes.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] A very small temporal integration time (264 μs) allows localization of multiple targets at varying distances.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Localization adaptations include pronounced asymmetry of the skull, nasal sacks, and specialized lipid structures in the forehead and jaws, as well as acoustically isolated middle and inner ears.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] The term 'binaural' literally signifies 'to hear with two ears', and was introduced in 1859 to signify the practice of listening to the same sound through both ears, or to two discrete sounds, one through each ear.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] It was not until 1916 that Carl Stumpf (1848–1936), a German philosopher and psychologist, distinguished between dichotic listening, which refers to the stimulation of each ear with a different stimulus, and diotic listening, the simultaneous stimulation of both ears with the same stimulus.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Later, it would become apparent that binaural hearing, whether dichotic or diotic, is the means by which sound localization occurs.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Scientific consideration of binaural hearing began before the phenomenon was so named, with speculations published in 1792 by William Charles Wells (1757–1817) based on his research into binocular vision.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Giovanni Battista Venturi (1746–1822) conducted and described experiments in which people tried to localize a sound using both ears, or one ear blocked with a finger.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] This work was not followed up on, and was only recovered after others had worked out how human sound localization works.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Lord Rayleigh (1842–1919) would do these same experiments and come to the results, without knowing Venturi had first done them, almost seventy-five years later.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Charles Wheatstone (1802–1875) did work on optics and color mixing, and also explored hearing.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] He invented a device he called a "microphone" that involved a metal plate over each ear, each connected to metal rods; he used this device to amplify sound.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] He also did experiments holding tuning forks to both ears at the same time, or separately, trying to work out how sense of hearing works, that he published in 1827.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Ernst Heinrich Weber (1795–1878) and August Seebeck (1805–1849) and William Charles Wells also attempted to compare and contrast what would become known as binaural hearing with the principles of binocular integration generally.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Understanding how the differences in sound signals between two ears contributes to auditory processing in such a way as to enable sound localization and direction was considerably advanced after the invention of the stethophone by Somerville Scott Alison in 1859, who coined the term 'binaural'.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-localization] Alison based the stethophone on the stethoscope, which had been invented by René Théophile Hyacinthe Laennec (1781–1826); the stethophone had two separate "pickups", allowing the user to hear and compare sounds derived from two discrete locations.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] A sound wave in a transmission medium causes a deviation (sound pressure, a *dynamic* pressure) in the local ambient pressure, a *static* pressure.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] In a sound wave, the complementary variable to sound pressure is the particle velocity.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Together, they determine the sound intensity of the wave.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] This relationship is an *inverse-proportional law*.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] which is often considered as the threshold of human hearing (roughly the sound of a mosquito flying 3 m away).
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] The proper notations for sound pressure level using this reference are *L**p*/(20 μPa) or *L**p* (re 20 μPa), but the suffix notations dB SPL, dB(SPL), dBSPL, and dBSPL are very common, even if they are not accepted by the SI.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Most sound-level measurements will be made relative to this reference, meaning 1 Pa will equal an SPL of $20\log _{10}\left({\frac {1}{2\times 10^{-5}}}\right)~{\text{dB}}\approx 94~{\text{dB}}$ .
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] In other media, such as underwater, a reference level of 1 μPa is used.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] These references are defined in ANSI S1.1-2013.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] The main instrument for measuring sound levels in the environment is the sound level meter.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Most sound level meters provide readings in A, C, and Z-weighted decibels and must meet international standards such as IEC 61672-2013.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] The lower limit of audibility is defined as SPL of 0 dB, but the upper limit is not as clearly defined.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Human hearing does not have a flat spectral sensitivity (frequency response) relative to frequency versus amplitude.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Humans do not perceive low- and high-frequency sounds as well as they perceive sounds between 3,000 and 4,000 Hz, as shown in the equal-loudness contour.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Because the frequency response of human hearing changes with amplitude, three weightings have been established for measuring sound pressure: A, B and C.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] In order to distinguish the different sound measures, a suffix is used: A-weighted sound pressure level is written either as dBA or LA, B-weighted sound pressure level is written either as dBB or LB, and C-weighted sound pressure level is written either as dBC or LC.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Unweighted sound pressure level is called "linear sound pressure level" and is often written as dBL or just L.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Some sound measuring instruments use the letter "Z" as an indication of linear SPL.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] The distance of the measuring microphone from a sound source is often omitted when SPL measurements are quoted, making the data useless, due to the inherent effect of the inverse proportional law.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] In the case of ambient environmental measurements of "background" noise, distance need not be quoted, as no single source is present, but when measuring the noise level of a specific piece of equipment, the distance should always be stated.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] A distance of one metre (1 m) from the source is a frequently used standard distance.
[src:spatial-audio-hrtf/sound-pressure] Because of the effects of reflected noise within a closed room, the use of an anechoic chamber allows sound to be comparable to measurements made in a free field environment.
